Step 7

This line:

return [
    Document(
        page_content=row[0],
        metadata=row[1] or {}
    )
    for row in rows
]

Transforms tuples into LangChain Documents.

⸻

Before:

(
  "Policy Number: POL123",
  {"chunk":5}
)

After:

Document(
   page_content="Policy Number: POL123",
   metadata={"chunk":5}
)

⸻

Why use Document objects?

Because LangChain standardizes retrieved content.

Instead of:

row[0]
row[1]

you can use:

doc.page_content
doc.metadata

Much cleaner.

⸻

What process_retrieval_pg receives

After:

docs = vectordb.similarity_search(
    "policy_number",
    13
)

docs contains:

[
 Document(
   page_content="Policy Number: POL123",
   metadata={"chunk":5}
 ),
 Document(
   page_content="Named Insured: ABC Corp",
   metadata={"chunk":6}
 )
]

Then your code does:

context = "\n".join(
    d.page_content
    for d in docs
)

Result:

Policy Number: POL123
Named Insured: ABC Corp

And THAT is what is sent to the LLM.

⸻

So the complete flow of similarity_search() is:

Attribute
(policy_number)
       ↓
embed_query()
       ↓
Query Vector
       ↓
Compare against ALL chunk vectors
inside REF123
       ↓
Sort by similarity (<=>)
       ↓
Take Top K
       ↓
Return chunk text
       ↓
Build Context
       ↓
Send Context to LLM

Notice something very important:

The LLM never sees the embeddings.

Embeddings are only used by PGVector to find relevant chunks.

The LLM only receives human-readable text from those chunks. That’s one of the biggest RAG concepts to remember.
